A Server-Side Template Injection (SSTI) vulnerability occurs when an application unsafely embeds user-supplied input directly into a server-side template engine, allowing an attacker to inject malicious template directives. Instead of treating the input as plain text, the template engine processes it as code, enabling the attacker to execute arbitrary commands, read sensitive files, or fully compromise the back-end server.

